  "prompt": "Which mathematician solved the magic square problem?",
  "response": "The concept of magic squares has a long history, and many mathematicians have contributed to its development over the centuries. The earliest known records of magic squares date back to ancient China, around 190 BCE, with the \"Lo Shu Square.\" However, the first systematic study of magic squares is often attributed to the Persian mathematician and astronomer Al-Biruni in the 10th century.\n\nLater, in the 16th century, European mathematicians such as Simon de la Loub\u00e8re and Bernard Frenicle de Bessy made significant contributions to the theory of magic squares. Frenicle de Bessy is particularly noted for his work on classifying magic squares of order 4.\n\nIn modern times, the study of magic squares has continued with contributions from numerous mathematicians, and the problem of constructing magic squares has been thoroughly explored and solved for various orders. Therefore, it is not accurate to attribute the solution of the magic square problem to a single mathematician, as it has been a cumulative effort over many centuries.",
